                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d583">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 800.51/3b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-04T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 4, 1919—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>154. For Glass from Davis. With further reference to your cable of December
                        31st<note n="55" xml:id="d583fn55">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_547">p. 547</ref>.</note> and
                    my reply of today [<hi rend="italic">yesterday</hi>]<note n="56"
                        xml:id="d583fn56">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_552">p. 552</ref>.</note> I
                    assume your position that all questions with reference to our foreign loans
                    should be discussed and disposed of in Washington does not exclude a discussion
                    study and recommendation in respect to the requirements and applications for
                    loans for relief.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Am</hi>[<hi rend="smallcaps">erican</hi>] <hi
                        rend="smallcaps">Mission</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
